Hey Lesli.

The best way is to add a CSS rule to override this.  You can do this by creating a new preset in the global CSS.  Then add a media rule.  This rule will override your existing CSS setting to adapt to the screen size.  I provide code for you to try out.

@media screen and (min-width: 315px) {
p { font-size: 60%;
}
}
This is a great rule to implement as it lets you override the existing CSS to adjust to certain conditions.  What I did here was I 'told' the responsive settings to be on the lookout for the conditions I set.  As soon as the screen size hits 315px this rule will target the font size of the paragraph for example.  This is a very basic example and you can play with it adding different rules and elements to see hoe they will act.
To target different elements you will have to us h1 -h6 for headings, p stands for paragraph, nav will be for navigation.  Nav could also be navigation depending on what was used to define the element.
Please let me know if you need more help.

